<sn><md>### Uses: Parallel Actions Continue in Past {.fg-red .text-end}

The word **==while==** is a common indicator for this kind of tense.

#### While I was doing my work, my wife had been cooking food (❌)

* Both actions occur **parallelly** in the past and **while** is a common indicator, so both clauses should be in **past continuous** form.
* Ans: While I was doing my work, my wife `was cooking` food (✅)

---

#### While she had been singing, I was singing (❌)

* Both actions occur **parallelly** in the past and **while** is a common indicator, so both clauses should be in **past continuous** form.
* Ans: While `she was singing`, I was singing (✅)
</md></sn><sn><md>## Long / Short Action


:::.bar
##### If two action occur in past,then the longer one should be in continuos form and the shorter one shoul be in past simple form

+++ see diagram
![diagram-of-long-short-action](https://i.imgur.com/38Uqlj6.png)
+++
:::

### Example

* I `was watching` T.V,when my father `came`.
* When my father `came`,I `was watching` T.V.

---

#### When the driver arrived,he had been reading newspaper. (❌)
* When the driver `arrived`,he `was reading` newspaper.(✅)
  * both action occur in past
  * the driver arrived - short action
  * he was reading nespaper - long action


